ow \$c\$ {\textbackslash}\& high \${\textbackslash}lambda\$. High cadence tracking shows subhaloes are dynamic residents, with \$25{\textbackslash}\%\$ leaving their host halo momentarily, becoming a backsplash subhalo, and another \$20{\textbackslash}\%\$ changing hosts entirely, in agreement with previous studies. In general, subhaloes have elliptical orbits, \$e{\textbackslash}approx0.6\$, with periods of \$2.3{\textasciicircum}\{+2.1\}\_\{-1.7\}\${\textasciitilde}Gyrs. Subhaloes lose most of their mass at pericentric passage with mass loss rates of \${\textbackslash}sim40{\textbackslash}\%\${\textasciitilde}Gyr\${\textasciicircum}\{-1\}\$. These catalogues will be made publicly available.},
