	abstract = {We derive the low redshift galaxy stellar mass function (GSMF), inclusive of dust corrections, for the equatorial Galaxy And Mass Assembly (GAMA) dataset covering 180 deg\${\textasciicircum}2\$. We construct the mass function using a density-corrected maximum volume method, using masses corrected for the impact of optically thick and thin dust. We explore the galactic bivariate brightness plane (\$M\_{\textbackslash}star-{\textbackslash}mu\$), demonstrating that surface brightness effects do not systematically bias our mass function measurement above 10\${\textasciicircum}\{7.5\}\$ M\$\_\{{\textbackslash}odot\}\$. The galaxy distribution in the \$M-{\textbackslash}mu\$-plane appears well bounded, indicating that no substantial population of massive but diffuse or highly compact galaxies are systematically missed due to the GAMA selection criteria. The GSMF is \{fit with\} a double Schechter function, with \${\textbackslash}mathcal M{\textasciicircum}{\textbackslash}star=10{\textasciicircum}\{10.78{\textbackslash}pm0.01{\textbackslash}pm0.20\}M\_{\textbackslash}odot\$, \${\textbackslash}phi{\textasciicircum}{\textbackslash}star\_1=(2.93{\textbackslash}pm0.40){\textbackslash}times10{\textasciicircum}\{-3\}h\_\{70\}{\textasciicircum}3\$Mpc\${\textasciicircum}\{-3\}\$, \${\textbackslash}alpha\_1=-0.62{\textbackslash}pm0.03{\textbackslash}pm0.15\$, \${\textbackslash}phi{\textasciicircum}{\textbackslash}star\_2=(0.63{\textbackslash}pm0.10){\textbackslash}times10{\textasciicircum}\{-3\}h\_\{70\}{\textasciicircum}3\$Mpc\${\textasciicircum}\{-3\}\$, and \${\textbackslash}alpha\_2=-1.50{\textbackslash}pm0.01{\textbackslash}pm0.15\$. We find the equivalent faint end slope as previously estimated using the GAMA-I sample, although we find a higher value of \${\textbackslash}mathcal M{\textasciicircum}{\textbackslash}star\$. Using the full GAMA-II sample, we are able to fit the mass function to masses as low as \$10{\textasciicircum}\{7.5\}\$ \$M\_{\textbackslash}odot\$, and assess limits to \$10{\textasciicircum}\{6.5\}\$ \$M\_{\textbackslash}odot\$. Combining GAMA-II with data from G10-COSMOS we are able to comment qualitatively on the shape of the GSMF down to masses as low as \$10{\textasciicircum}\{6\}\$ \$M\_{\textbackslash}odot\$. Beyond the well known upturn seen in the GSMF at \$10{\textasciicircum}\{9.5\}\$ the distribution appears to maintain a single power-law slope from \$10{\textasciicircum}9\$ to \$10{\textasciicircum}\{6.5\}\$. We calculate the stellar mass density parameter given our best-estimate GSMF, finding \${\textbackslash}Omega\_{\textbackslash}star= 1.66{\textasciicircum}\{+0.24\}\_\{-0.23\}{\textbackslash}pm0.97 h{\textasciicircum}\{-1\}\_\{70\} {\textbackslash}times 10{\textasciicircum}\{-3\}\$, inclusive of random and systematic uncertainties.},
