	abstract = {We measure the evolution of the stellar mass function (SMF) from z=0-1 using multi-wavelength imaging and spectroscopic redshifts from the PRism MUlti-object Survey (PRIMUS) and the Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS). From PRIMUS we construct an i{\textless}23 flux-limited sample of {\textasciitilde}40,000 galaxies at z=0.2-1.0 over five fields totaling {\textasciitilde}5.5 deg{\textasciicircum}2, and from the SDSS we select {\textasciitilde}170,000 galaxies at z=0.01-0.2 that we analyze consistently with respect to PRIMUS to minimize systematic errors in our evolutionary measurements. We find that the SMF of all galaxies evolves relatively little since z=1, although we do find evidence for mass assembly downsizing; we measure a {\textasciitilde}30\% increase in the number density of {\textasciitilde}10{\textasciicircum}10 Msun galaxies since z{\textasciitilde}0.6, and a {\textless}10\% change in the number density of all {\textgreater}10{\textasciicircum}11 Msun galaxies since z{\textasciitilde}1. Dividing the sample into star-forming and quiescent using an evolving cut in specific star-formation rate, we find that the number density of {\textasciitilde}10{\textasciicircum}10 Msun star-forming galaxies stays relatively constant since z{\textasciitilde}0.6, whereas the space-density of {\textgreater}10{\textasciicircum}11 Msun star-forming galaxies decreases by {\textasciitilde}50\% between z{\textasciitilde}1 and z{\textasciitilde}0. Meanwhile, the number density of {\textasciitilde}10{\textasciicircum}10 Msun quiescent galaxies increases steeply towards low redshift, by a factor of {\textasciitilde}2-3 since z{\textasciitilde}0.6, while the number of massive quiescent galaxies remains approximately constant since z{\textasciitilde}1. These results suggest that the rate at which star-forming galaxies are quenched increases with decreasing stellar mass, but that the bulk of the stellar mass buildup within the quiescent population occurs around {\textasciitilde}10{\textasciicircum}10.8 Msun. In addition, we conclude that mergers do not appear to be a dominant channel for the stellar mass buildup of galaxies at z{\textless}1, even among massive ({\textgreater}10{\textasciicircum}11 Msun) quiescent galaxies.},
