	abstract = {Previous studies of fueling black holes (BHs) in galactic nuclei have argued (on scales {\textasciitilde}0.01-1000pc) accretion is dynamical with inflow rates \${\textbackslash}dot\{M\}{\textbackslash}sim{\textbackslash}eta{\textbackslash},M\_\{{\textbackslash}rm gas\}/t\_\{{\textbackslash}rm dyn\}\$ in terms of gas mass \$M\_\{{\textbackslash}rm gas\}\$, dynamical time \$t\_\{{\textbackslash}rm dyn\}\$, and some \${\textbackslash}eta\$. But these models generally neglected expulsion of gas by stellar feedback, or considered extremely high densities where expulsion is inefficient. Studies of star formation, however, have shown on sub-kpc scales the expulsion efficiency \$f\_\{{\textbackslash}rm wind\}=M\_\{{\textbackslash}rm ejected\}/M\_\{{\textbackslash}rm total\}\$ scales with the gravitational acceleration as \$(1-f\_\{{\textbackslash}rm wind\})/f\_\{{\textbackslash}rm wind\}{\textbackslash}sim{\textbackslash}bar\{a\}\_\{{\textbackslash}rm grav\}/{\textbackslash}langle{\textbackslash}dot\{p\}/m\_\{{\textbackslash}ast\}{\textbackslash}rangle{\textbackslash}sim {\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm eff\}/{\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm crit\}\$ where \${\textbackslash}bar\{a\}\_\{{\textbackslash}rm grav\}{\textbackslash}equiv G{\textbackslash},M\_\{{\textbackslash}rm tot\}({\textless}r)/r{\textasciicircum}\{2\}\$ and \${\textbackslash}langle{\textbackslash}dot\{p\}/m\_\{{\textbackslash}ast\}{\textbackslash}rangle\$ is the momentum injection rate from young stars. Adopting this as the simplest correction for stellar feedback, \${\textbackslash}eta {\textbackslash}rightarrow {\textbackslash}eta{\textbackslash},(1-f\_\{{\textbackslash}rm wind\})\$, we show this provides a more accurate description of simulations with stellar feedback at low densities. This has immediate consequences, predicting e.g. the slope and normalization of the \$M-{\textbackslash}sigma\$ and \$M-M\_\{{\textbackslash}rm bulge\}\$ relation, \$L\_\{{\textbackslash}rm AGN\}-\$SFR relations, and explanations for outliers in compact Es. Most strikingly, because star formation simulations show expulsion is efficient (\$f\_\{{\textbackslash}rm wind\}{\textbackslash}sim1\$) below total-mass surface density \$M\_\{{\textbackslash}rm tot\}/{\textbackslash}pi{\textbackslash},r{\textasciicircum}\{2\}{\textless}{\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm crit\}{\textbackslash}sim3{\textbackslash}times10{\textasciicircum}\{9\}{\textbackslash},M\_\{{\textbackslash}odot\}{\textbackslash},\{{\textbackslash}rm kpc{\textasciicircum}\{-2\}\}\$ (where \${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm crit\}={\textbackslash}langle{\textbackslash}dot\{p\}/m\_\{{\textbackslash}ast\}{\textbackslash}rangle/({\textbackslash}pi{\textbackslash},G)\$), BH mass is predicted to specifically trace host galaxy properties above a critical surface brightness \${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{{\textbackslash}rm crit\}\$ (B-band \${\textbackslash}mu\_\{{\textbackslash}rm B\}{\textasciicircum}\{{\textbackslash}rm crit\}{\textbackslash}sim 19{\textbackslash},\{{\textbackslash}rm mag{\textbackslash},arcsec{\textasciicircum}\{-2\}\}\$). This naturally explains why BH masses preferentially reflect bulge properties or central surface-densities (\${\textbackslash}Sigma\_\{1{\textbackslash},\{{\textbackslash}rm kpc\}\}\$), not 'total' galaxy properties.},
