	abstract = {Recent work indicates that the nearby Galactic halo is dominated by the debris from a major accretion event. We confirm that result from an analysis of APOGEE-DR14 element abundances and \${\textbackslash}textit\{Gaia\}\$-DR2 kinematics of halo stars. We show that \${\textbackslash}sim\$2/3 of nearby halo stars have high orbital eccentricities (\$e {\textbackslash}gtrsim 0.8\$), and abundance patterns typical of massive Milky Way dwarf galaxy satellites today, characterised by relatively low [Fe/H], [Mg/Fe], [Al/Fe], and [Ni/Fe]. The trend followed by high \$e\$ stars in the [Mg/Fe]-[Fe/H] plane shows a change of slope at [Fe/H]\${\textbackslash}sim-1.3\$, which is also typical of stellar populations from relatively massive dwarf galaxies. Low \$e\$ stars exhibit no such change of slope within the observed [Fe/H] range and show slightly higher abundances of Mg, Al and Ni. Unlike their low \$e\$ counterparts, high \$e\$ stars show slightly retrograde motion, make higher vertical excursions and reach larger apocentre radii. By comparing the position in [Mg/Fe]-[Fe/H] space of high \$e\$ stars with those of accreted galaxies from the EAGLE suite of cosmological simulations we constrain the mass of the accreted satellite to be in the range \$10{\textasciicircum}\{8.5\}{\textbackslash}lesssim M\_*{\textbackslash}lesssim 10{\textasciicircum}\{9\}{\textbackslash}mathrm\{M\_{\textbackslash}odot\}\$. We show that the median orbital eccentricities of debris are largely unchanged since merger time, implying that this accretion event likely happened at \$z{\textbackslash}lesssim1.5\$. The exact nature of the low \$e\$ population is unclear, but we hypothesise that it is a combination of \${\textbackslash}textit\{in situ\}\$ star formation, high \${\textbar}z{\textbar}\$ disc stars, lower mass accretion events, and contamination by the low \$e\$ tail of the high \$e\$ population. Finally, our results imply that the accretion history of the Milky Way was quite unusual.},
