	url = {http://arxiv.org/abs/1601.07905},
	doi = {10.3847/0004-637X/821/1/5},
	abstract = {We study the mass spectrum of destroyed dwarfs that contribute to the accreted stellar mass of Milky Way (MW) mass M\_vir {\textasciitilde} 10{\textasciicircum}12.1 M\_sun) halos using a suite of 45 zoom-in, dissipationless simulations. Empirical models are employed to relate (peak) subhalo mass to dwarf stellar mass, and we use constraints from z=0 observations and hydrodynamical simulations to estimate the metallicity distribution of the accreted stellar material. The dominant contributors to the accreted stellar mass are relatively massive dwarfs with M\_star {\textasciitilde} 10{\textasciicircum}8-10{\textasciicircum}10 M\_sun. Halos with more quiescent accretion histories tend to have lower mass progenitors (10{\textasciicircum}8-10{\textasciicircum}9 M\_sun), and lower overall accreted stellar masses. Ultra-faint mass (M\_star {\textless} 10{\textasciicircum}5 M\_sun) dwarfs contribute a negligible amount ({\textless}{\textless} 1\%) to the accreted stellar mass and, despite having low average metallicities, supply a small fraction ({\textasciitilde}2-5 \%) of the very metal-poor stars with [Fe/H] {\textless} -2. Dwarfs with masses 10{\textasciicircum}5 {\textless} M\_star/M\_sun {\textless} 10{\textasciicircum}8 provide a substantial amount of the very metal-poor stellar material ({\textasciitilde}40-80 \%), and even relatively metal-rich dwarfs with M\_star {\textgreater} 10{\textasciicircum}8 M\_sun can contribute a considerable fraction ({\textasciitilde}20-60 \%) of metal-poor stars if their metallicity distributions have significant metal-poor tails. Finally, we find that the generic assumption of a quiescent assembly history for the MW halo seems to be in tension with the mass spectrum of its surviving dwarfs. We suggest that the MW could be a "transient fossil"; a quiescent halo with a recent accretion event(s) that disguises the preceding formation history of the halo.},
